ransformations from the eighteenth century in the Mediterranean Sea, its original birthplace. The new epidemics of cholera and the development of bacteriology and hygiene, European colonial expansion, the intensification of commercial interchanges, the technological revolution in maritime and land transportation and the modernisation policies in Islamic countries were among the main factors behind such transformations. The book focuses on case studies on the European and Islamic shores of the Mediterranean showing the multidimensional nature of quarantine, the intimate links that sanitary administrations and institutions had with the territorial organisation of states, international trade, political regimes and the construction of national, colonial and professional identities  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedicinexHistoryy18th century. 0aQuarantinexLaw and legislationzMediterranean RegionxHistory. 0aQuarantinexPolitical aspectszMediterranean RegionxHistory. 0aQuarantinezMediterranean RegionxHistory. 0aQuarantine-History. 0aQuarantine-Law and legislation-Mediterranean Region-History. 0aQuarantine-Mediterranean Region-History. 0aQuarantine-Political aspects-Mediterranean Region-History. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aIdentity.  aLong 19th century.  aMediterranean.  aPower.  aQuarantine.  aSpace.1 aAbreu, Laurinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArrizabalaga, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBon, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonastra, Quim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChircop, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChircop, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator